 "awd_abstract_narration": "9321547  Key  This three-year program will quantify the individual energy  streams that make up the arctic surface radiation budget, and will  relate the observed radiation distribution to synoptic-scale wind,  pressure, and moisture patterns.  It will be the first effort to  produce a comprehensive radiation climatology for the Arctic.    The arctic surface energy budget, particularly that of the Arctic  Ocean, has been identified as a major component of the global  climate system that is potentially sensitive to climate-scale  perturbations due to feedback mechanisms involving the surface  albedo, the stability of the lower troposphere, and water vapor  transport.    The project includes four main tasks: (1) The analysis of solar and  long-wave radiation data obtained directly at manned observing  sites in the arctic.  (2) The calculation of radiative fluxes at the  surface and at the top of the atmosphere using a satellite-based  cloud data product from the International Satellite Cloud  Climatology Project (ISCCP).  (3) For selected months, the  ISCCP-derived fluxes will be compared to the corresponding  synoptic regime, and (4) a study to assess the effects of the  sampling and analysis procedure on the radiation statistics and their  temporal variability will be undertaken.  ***",
